name.text: 8.2.15 (Example of finding number of terms in a sum)

questiontext.text:
We do not always know at the outset how many terms are in the sum. The following example shows how to obtain this information.

Example

How many terms are there in the sequence \(2,5,8,\dots,326\)?

Solution

Here, the common difference is \(5-2 = 8-5 = \cdots = 3\). Now notice that to get from \(2\) to \(326\) we have added \(326-2=324 = 108 \times 3\). This means that we have added \(d\) \(108\) times. Therefore including the initial term, there are \(109\) terms in the sequence.
